    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Non-cannulated construct compression-bending prediction",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/valresult/construct-stiffness-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Construct stiffness QoI comparison — FEA vs. experimental (N=11)",
      "description": "FEA-predicted construct stiffness was compared against experimental measurements from 11 non-cannulated pedicle screw constructs tested at two independent laboratories under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending protocol. The ensemble mean FEA prediction differed from the experimental mean by 4.2%, well within the pre-established 10% acceptance bound. The normalised error metric E/uval was 0.87, satisfying the E/uval < 1.96 criterion. Measurement uncertainty was propagated from material property distributions (Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus CV = 1.8%), geometric tolerances (±0.05 mm), and boundary condition variability (fixture compliance ±3%). The simulation campaign was executed in Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 using a mesh of approximately 420 000 second-order tetrahedral elements; mesh convergence was confirmed at the 0.5% energy norm criterion. Laboratory testing was conducted by DePuy Synthes Product Development and independently replicated by the FDA Office of Science and Engineering Laboratories. Both laboratories reported stiffness values within 2.1% of each other, confirming inter-laboratory reproducibility. The detailed test protocol, raw load-displacement curves, and reduced stiffness values are archived in the project data package. This result constitutes the primary quantitative evidence supporting the credibility claim that the FEA framework adequately represents the compression-bending stiffness response of the non-cannulated construct.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/data/f1717-bench-test-n11-lab1"
    },
